
// ======================================================================
// 			COMPILER FOR NANOMORPHO
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------
// This is the development version of the NanoMorpho programming language.
// This project can be built from source and tested in terminal.
// 
// See handbok.pdf for more info on NanoMorpho.
//
//						Andrea Björk Björnsdóttir
//							       April 2016
// ======================================================================

Linux instructions:

Extract folder into desired location.

cd into nanomorpho/source and do:

% make

After that you can write project files <filename>.nm in the Workspace
folder and to compile them, do

% ./nanomorpho.sh -c <filename>.nm

and run them from the Workspace with

% ./nanomorpho.sh <filename>


Of course, if you would like to create a symbolic link from the nanomorpho folder you can do so with

% sudo ln -s Workspace/nanomorpho.sh /usr/local/bin/nanomorpho

and then simply compile and run using:

% nanomorpho -c <filename>.nm
% nanomorpho <filename>


// ===============================
// Manual compilation from source: 
// ===============================

If you need to compile separately the jflex, byaccj and java files, you can do so with the following commands:

Jflex:

% java -jar jflex-1.6.0.jar nanomorpho.jflex

byacc:

% ./yacc.linux -J -Jclass=NanoMorphoParser -v nanomorpho.byaccj

Java compile:

javac NanoMorphoLexer.java NanoMorphoParser.java NanoMorphoParserVal.java

// =======================================================
// Manual compilation and running of nanomorpho programs :
// =======================================================

java NanoMorphoParser example.nm

This will create example.masm, compile that with morpho:

java -jar morpho.jar -c example.masm

This will create example.mexe which can be run with Morpho:

java -jar morpho.jar example


